; ============================================================
; SECTION 1 — The question, sharpened
; ============================================================

(section :n 1 :title "The question, sharpened"

  :prose "
There are two distinct research questions that get confused with each
other, and I want to keep them apart before doing anything else.

**Philosophy ABOUT computation** — the meta-topic. Philosophy of mind
asking whether a Turing machine can think. Extended mind theses (Clark
and Chalmers, 'The Extended Mind,' Analysis 58, 1998) asking whether
a notebook counts as part of cognition. Embodied cognition (Varela,
Thompson, Rosch, _The Embodied Mind_, MIT Press 1991) asking whether
disembodied symbol shuffling can produce understanding. Searle's
Chinese Room (Searle, 'Minds, Brains, and Programs,' Behavioral and
Brain Sciences 3, 1980) asking whether syntactic manipulation ever
becomes semantics. These are important — Sakura's Book of LLM
Philosophy carries them — but they are ABOUT the computer, from
outside it. They do not become running code. They are essays that
comment on running code.

**Philosophy AS computation** — the focus of this document. A
philosophical claim, method, or artifact expressed such that the
program IS the philosophical work. Kant's categorical imperative
written as a rule engine that will actually classify a proposed
maxim as universalizable-or-not. Aristotle's practical syllogism as
a function that, given premises and a character trait, produces the
appropriate action. Peirce's abduction not as prose describing what
abduction is, but as an executable inference procedure that, given
evidence, produces best-explanation hypotheses. Bentham's felicific
calculus as a numeric utility function you can actually run and
argue with the results of.

The claim I want to defend across this document: **a very large
fraction of Western philosophy — and significant parts of non-Western
traditions — produces artifacts that a Scheme-family programming
language can express with unusual fidelity.** Not everything. Ordinary-
language philosophy in the Austin/Wittgenstein-late sense famously
resists formalization; that's part of its point. Continental
philosophy in the Derrida/Deleuze mode operates on text in ways a
formal language can imitate but not exhaust. But logic, formal
semantics, decision theory, deontic ethics, argumentation theory,
much of philosophy of language, and every philosophical tradition
that produced a syllogism or a rule — all of it becomes code
naturally.

The rest of this document is a survey of those categories, with
citations to real primary sources, and a mapping to which of the 16
philosophers on Sakura's roster produces which code-shaped artifact.
")

; -- write checkpoint 1 --

; ============================================================
; SECTION 2 — Categories of philosophical work that becomes code
; ============================================================

(section :n 2 :title "Categories of philosophical work that becomes code"

  :prose "
This is the main survey. Each subsection covers a distinct tradition
or research programme, with the specific artifacts it produces, the
primary sources you would translate FROM, and where the resulting
code lives most naturally in a Scheme-family language.
")

; ------------------------------------------------------------
; 2.A — Logic and formal reasoning
; ------------------------------------------------------------

(subsection :id 2.a :title "Logic and formal reasoning"

  :prose "
Logic is where philosophy first became computable, and it is still the
category with the highest yield of code-shaped artifacts. Every branch
below has been implemented in Scheme, Prolog, ML, or Coq at least once,
and the implementations are short enough to teach.

**Propositional logic.** Truth tables, satisfiability (SAT), semantic
tableaux (Beth 1955; Smullyan, _First-Order Logic_, Springer 1968).
A propositional SAT solver in Scheme using DPLL (Davis, Putnam,
Logemann, Loveland, 'A Machine Program for Theorem-Proving,' CACM
5:394, 1962) is about 100 lines. It is the foundation of every
model-checker in production today.

**First-order logic.** Quantifiers, unification (Robinson, 'A
Machine-Oriented Logic Based on the Resolution Principle,' JACM 12,
1965), resolution theorem proving. Frege's _Begriffsschrift_ (1879)
is where quantified logic was born. In Scheme, a resolution prover
over Horn clauses is a hundred lines; over full FOL, a few hundred.
John Harrison's _Handbook of Practical Logic and Automated Reasoning_
(Cambridge 2009) is the modern reference; every algorithm in it
translates directly.

**Modal logic.** Necessity and possibility operators (Box and Diamond).
Kripke semantics — worlds and accessibility relations — from Kripke's
'Semantical Considerations on Modal Logic' (Acta Philosophica Fennica
16, 1963). The systems K, T, S4, S5 are all defined by restrictions
on the accessibility relation, which in code is just a graph. A
Scheme representation: worlds as symbols, accessibility as a list of
(world . world) pairs, evaluation of Box-phi at world w = phi holds
at every world w' such that (w . w') is accessible. About 40 lines.

**Deontic logic.** Modal logic with the O (obligation), P (permission),
F (forbidden) operators. Von Wright, 'Deontic Logic,' Mind 60, 1951.
Immediate application: representing rules like 'a promise to X
obligates delivering X unless X is impossible' and detecting
conflicts of obligation. Nute, _Defeasible Deontic Logic_ (Kluwer
1997) collects the modern variants.

**Temporal logic.** Linear temporal logic (LTL) and computation tree
logic (CTL), from Pnueli's 'The Temporal Logic of Programs' (FOCS 18,
1977) and Clarke and Emerson's model-checking work (Logic of Programs,
1981). LTL formulas talk about eventuality (F), always (G), next (X),
until (U). Model checking is what verifies real hardware and software
today; it fits in a chapter of Scheme.

**Intuitionistic logic.** Heyting's formalization of Brouwer's
constructivism (Heyting, _Intuitionism: An Introduction_, North-Holland
1956). The Curry-Howard correspondence (Curry 1934; Howard 1969) makes
this immediately code-shaped: a proof in intuitionistic logic IS a
term in the simply-typed lambda calculus, and vice versa. Coq, Agda,
Lean, Idris all rest on this. Every proof in Coq is a functional
program. Sakura Scheme cannot host dependent types natively, but it
can host an intuitionistic natural-deduction checker easily.

**Paraconsistent logic.** Handling contradictions without explosion
(ex falso quodlibet). Da Costa's C-systems (Da Costa, 'On the Theory
of Inconsistent Formal Systems,' Notre Dame Journal of Formal Logic
15, 1974); Priest, _In Contradiction_ (Oxford, 2nd ed. 2006). Useful
whenever you have a knowledge base that will contain contradictions
(any real one). Priest's LP (logic of paradox) has a three-valued
semantics — true, false, both — that fits in a truth-table extension.

**Non-monotonic logic.** Default reasoning (Reiter, 'A Logic for
Default Reasoning,' Artificial Intelligence 13, 1980), circumscription
(McCarthy, 'Circumscription — A Form of Non-Monotonic Reasoning,'
Artificial Intelligence 13, 1980), autoepistemic logic (Moore, 1985).
The frame problem and the qualification problem live here. In Scheme
this is a rule-engine with priorities and defeaters — approximately
the pattern PAIP Ch 12 (Norvig 1992) uses for scripts and frames.

**Fuzzy logic.** Zadeh, 'Fuzzy Sets,' Information and Control 8, 1965.
Truth as a number in [0,1] with min/max for conjunction/disjunction.
Two hundred lines of Scheme gives you a fuzzy inference engine that
can control a thermostat.

**Category theory.** Not a logic in the traditional sense, but the
mathematics that unified logic, computation, and structure in the
late 20th century. Mac Lane, _Categories for the Working
Mathematician_ (Springer 1971). Arrows and composition ARE code —
in Haskell that's the Functor/Applicative/Monad ladder; in Scheme
it's the fold/map/bind pattern generalized. The category-theoretic
shape of monads (Moggi, 'Notions of Computation and Monads,'
Information and Computation 93, 1991) is directly implementable.

For a Scheme-first survey of most of the above, Sussman and Wisdom's
_Structure and Interpretation of Classical Mechanics_ (MIT Press
2001, 2nd ed. 2014) — SICM — demonstrates the symbolic-mathematics
end; PAIP demonstrates the logic-programming end; Pierce's _Types
and Programming Languages_ (MIT 2002) demonstrates the type-theory
end. Any of the systems above can be translated into Sakura Scheme
in a chapter.
")

; -- write checkpoint 2.a --

; ------------------------------------------------------------
; 2.B — Analytic philosophy and philosophy of language
; ------------------------------------------------------------

(subsection :id 2.b :title "Analytic philosophy and philosophy of language"

  :prose "
The analytic tradition in the twentieth century oriented itself around
the question 'what does a sentence mean?' — and answered in ways that
became formal enough to run.

**Truth-conditional semantics.** Tarski's 'The Concept of Truth in
Formalized Languages' (1935, English 1956, in _Logic, Semantics,
Metamathematics_) is the founding text. A Tarskian model for a formal
language, in Scheme, is a domain of individuals, an interpretation
function assigning predicates to sets and functions to functions, and
a satisfaction relation defined recursively over sentence structure.
The recursion is exactly the shape Scheme evaluates a program:
`(satisfies model formula environment)`. Donald Davidson's programme
(collected in _Inquiries into Truth and Interpretation_, Oxford 1984)
extends Tarskian truth to natural language and is the direct ancestor
of computational semantics.

**Montague grammar.** Richard Montague, 'The Proper Treatment of
Quantification in Ordinary English' (1973, in _Formal Philosophy_,
Yale 1974). Montague's claim — that natural language semantics is a
branch of mathematics, specifically the intensional logic he called
IL — is the direct progenitor of formal semantics as a working
research programme. Every Montague fragment is compilable to
lambda-terms, and the composition rule (function application at each
syntactic node) is a fold over the parse tree. Blackburn and Bos,
_Representation and Inference for Natural Language_ (CSLI 2005),
gives Prolog implementations; they port to Scheme in a chapter.

**Lambda calculus as a semantic device.** Church, 'A Formulation of
the Simple Theory of Types,' Journal of Symbolic Logic 5, 1940.
Alonzo Church invented the lambda calculus to serve as a foundation
for logic; it turned out to be a foundation for computation. Scheme
inherits it directly — every `(lambda (x) ...)` in Scheme is a
Church-style abstraction. Montague semantics uses lambda-terms as
its representation of noun-phrase and verb-phrase meanings. This is
the pivot: philosophy of language IS lambda calculus.

**Kripke semantics for modal operators.** Already covered under logic,
but worth noting the interpretive move: Kripke's possible-worlds
apparatus was philosophy first (Kripke, _Naming and Necessity_,
Harvard 1980) and became a widely-used computational tool second.
Every model-checker's semantics is Kripke's.

**Grice's cooperative principle.** Paul Grice, 'Logic and
Conversation' (in _Studies in the Way of Words_, Harvard 1989). The
four maxims — Quantity, Quality, Relation, Manner — and the machinery
of conversational implicature. A maxim-checker is a small rule engine:
given an utterance, its literal meaning, and the shared context, does
it violate a maxim in a way that generates implicature? Sperber and
Wilson's relevance-theoretic reformulation (_Relevance_, Blackwell
2nd ed. 1995) has been implemented as small dialogue systems. In
Scheme, ~150 lines gives you a Gricean assistant that flags its own
possible over- and under-informativity.

**Speech act theory.** Austin's _How to Do Things with Words_ (Oxford
1962) and Searle's _Speech Acts_ (Cambridge 1969) and _Expression and
Meaning_ (Cambridge 1979). Searle's taxonomy — assertives, directives,
commissives, expressives, declaratives — is a five-way classifier over
utterances. As code: given an utterance and a context, tag it. Simple
Bayesian classifier trained on tagged examples, or a rule system with
Searlean felicity conditions. Sakura's `read-utterance` cart is
already this.

**Meaning as use.** Wittgenstein-late, _Philosophical Investigations_
(1953). Notoriously, meaning-as-use is the philosophical position that
RESISTS formalization — Wittgenstein's whole point was that language
games are not rule systems that can be fully specified. But we can
model *a specific game* — the ordering game, the tea game, the
customer-service game — as a small state machine with allowed moves,
and let the resistance-to-full-formalization live at the joints where
one game hands off to another. This is the shape modern dialogue-
state tracking uses; see Young et al., 'POMDP-Based Statistical
Spoken Dialog Systems' (Proc. IEEE 101, 2013).

**Meaning postulates.** Carnap, _Meaning and Necessity_ (Chicago 1947)
introduced meaning postulates to capture analytic relations (all
bachelors are unmarried) as axioms. In Scheme these are just rules
in a knowledge base. WordNet's hyponymy and synonymy relations
(Fellbaum ed., _WordNet: An Electronic Lexical Database_, MIT 1998)
are meaning postulates at scale.

**Quine on translation and holism.** Quine, _Word and Object_ (MIT
1960); 'Two Dogmas of Empiricism' (Philosophical Review 60, 1951).
Quine's indeterminacy of translation is the philosophical claim that
undermines any hope of decoding utterances one-to-one from behavior.
It doesn't become code directly, but it shapes how you build a
translation system honestly — you accept that multiple translation
manuals will be empirically equivalent, and you rank them by other
criteria (simplicity, conservatism, coherence with prior mappings).
This is the pattern Bayesian machine translation systems now use.
")

; -- write checkpoint 2.b --

; ------------------------------------------------------------
; 2.C — Reasoning under uncertainty
; ------------------------------------------------------------

(subsection :id 2.c :title "Reasoning under uncertainty"

  :prose "
Once you accept that most real-world reasoning is not deductive,
uncertainty becomes the central technical problem. Every framework
here has a code implementation with real citations.

**Bayesian belief networks.** Judea Pearl, _Probabilistic Reasoning
in Intelligent Systems: Networks of Plausible Inference_ (Morgan
Kaufmann, 1988). Pearl's book is the philosophical AND computational
foundation of graphical models. A Bayesian network is a directed
acyclic graph of random variables with conditional probability
tables at each node; exact inference by variable elimination is
~200 lines of Scheme; approximate inference by likelihood weighting
or Gibbs sampling is another 100. Pearl won the 2011 Turing Award
for this work; his subsequent _Causality_ (Cambridge, 2nd ed. 2009)
extends the framework from correlation to intervention.

**Formal epistemology and belief revision.** The AGM postulates
(Alchourron, Gardenfors, Makinson, 'On the Logic of Theory Change,'
JSL 50, 1985) formalize what a rational agent does when new
information contradicts prior beliefs. Contract, revise, expand.
A belief-revision engine over a knowledge base of propositions is
a small (~200 line) Scheme program with clear philosophical content:
which of your current beliefs do you drop when a contradiction
arrives? The postulates say: drop as little as possible, prefer
dropping less-entrenched beliefs. Entrenchment is a partial order
the user supplies.

**Dempster-Shafer theory.** Shafer, _A Mathematical Theory of
Evidence_ (Princeton 1976). An alternative to Bayes: instead of a
single probability, you have a mass function over the power set of
outcomes. Useful when you cannot commit to a prior. In Scheme, mass
functions are association lists over sets-as-sorted-lists.

**Formal decision theory.** Savage, _The Foundations of Statistics_
(Wiley 1954); Jeffrey, _The Logic of Decision_ (McGraw-Hill 1965).
Expected utility calculators, given a probability distribution over
states and a utility function over outcomes. This is one-liner
Scheme once you have `stat/expected-value`. Where it gets
interesting philosophically is under Knightian uncertainty (Knight,
_Risk, Uncertainty, and Profit_, 1921) — decisions where you cannot
assign a probability distribution. Gilboa and Schmeidler's maxmin
expected utility (JMathEcon 18, 1989) is the standard response and
is ten more lines of Scheme.

**Non-monotonic reasoning as uncertainty.** Overlaps 2.A, but the
philosophical framing is different: default logic assumes 'birds
fly, absent contrary information,' which is an epistemic default
rather than a logical necessity. Bringing this into code gives you
a substantive stance on tacit-knowledge reasoning.
")

; -- write checkpoint 2.c --

; ------------------------------------------------------------
; 2.D — Ethics as executable
; ------------------------------------------------------------

(subsection :id 2.d :title "Ethics as executable"

  :prose "
Every major normative-ethical tradition has an executable shape.
This is one of the most productive areas for code-shaped philosophy,
partly because moral philosophy has always been drawn to
generalizable maxims, and generalizable maxims are rules.

**Deontological rule engines.** Kant, _Groundwork of the Metaphysics
of Morals_ (1785). The categorical imperative: 'Act only according
to that maxim by which you can at the same time will that it should
become a universal law.' As code: given a proposed maxim (a rule),
attempt to universalize it and check for contradiction — either
logical contradiction (perfect duty) or contradiction in the will
(imperfect duty). Real implementations exist; see Powers, 'Prospects
for a Kantian Machine' (IEEE Intelligent Systems 21, 2006), and
Anderson and Anderson's collected work _Machine Ethics_ (Cambridge
2011). Ross's prima facie duties (_The Right and the Good_, Oxford
1930) refine Kant into a multi-duty weighing engine — a small
priority queue.

**Utilitarian calculators.** Bentham's felicific calculus in _An
Introduction to the Principles of Morals and Legislation_ (1789)
enumerates seven dimensions: intensity, duration, certainty,
propinquity, fecundity, purity, extent. All numeric. A literal
implementation: for each proposed action, sum weighted-happiness
across affected parties. Mill's _Utilitarianism_ (1861) refines by
introducing higher- and lower-order pleasures. Peter Singer's
preference utilitarianism (_Practical Ethics_, Cambridge 3rd ed.
2011) substitutes preference-satisfaction for pleasure and is
straightforward to code once you have a preference-elicitation
verb.

**Virtue-ethics character models.** Aristotle, _Nicomachean Ethics_
(c. 340 BCE), and MacIntyre's _After Virtue_ (Notre Dame 1981).
Aristotle's ethos as a parameter vector — a character with traits
(courage, temperance, justice) each on a Golden-Mean spectrum
between deficiency and excess. Given a situation and a character
vector, the practical syllogism produces the appropriate action.
The 'phronetic agent' is a function from character-state and
situation to action; contemporary work on Aristotelian AI ethics
(Vallor, _Technology and the Virtues_, Oxford 2016) treats this
seriously.

**Trolley-problem simulators.** Foot, 'The Problem of Abortion and
the Doctrine of the Double Effect' (Oxford Review 5, 1967); Thomson,
'The Trolley Problem' (Yale LJ 94, 1985). Not just puzzles: they
are executable moral scenarios that let you compare deontological,
utilitarian, and virtue-ethical outputs on the same input. Awad et
al., 'The Moral Machine Experiment' (Nature 563, 2018) built one
at scale. In Scheme, a trolley scenario is a small state with
victims and actions; a moral engine is a function from state to
recommended action; multiple engines side-by-side give you a
lens comparison.

**Rawlsian fairness.** Rawls, _A Theory of Justice_ (Harvard 1971).
The veil of ignorance as an anonymization function: given a proposed
policy that assigns outcomes to identified individuals, hide the
identifiers and evaluate. The maximin principle (maximize the
minimum outcome across the anonymized population) becomes a
straightforward optimizer. Recent work in algorithmic fairness
(Dwork, Hardt, et al., 'Fairness Through Awareness,' ITCS 2012)
directly connects Rawls's philosophy to code-level guarantees.

**Levinasian obligation.** Levinas, _Totality and Infinity_ (Nijhoff
1961; English Duquesne 1969). The face of the Other as the
foundation of ethics — a claim that resists formalization but has
a shadow-shape in code: for every entity your program acts on,
require a step that asks 'have I encountered this entity as face,
or reduced it to a category?' A Levinasian check in a moral engine
prevents pure aggregation from steamrolling individuals. This is
what data-protection law (GDPR Article 22, human review of
automated decisions) codifies without naming Levinas.

**Ubuntu and relational ethics.** Ramose, _African Philosophy
Through Ubuntu_ (Mond Books 1999); Metz, 'Toward an African Moral
Theory' (Journal of Political Philosophy 15, 2007). 'A person is
a person through other persons' — ethics grounded in relational
networks rather than isolated agents. As code: obligations attach
to relationships, not individuals; the moral engine walks the
relationship graph. This is a natural fit for graph-native systems
like Cortex.

**Confucian role ethics.** Confucius, _Analects_ (compiled c. 500-200
BCE); Hall and Ames, _Thinking Through Confucius_ (SUNY 1987);
Ames and Rosemont, _The Analects of Confucius: A Philosophical
Translation_ (Ballantine 1998). Ethics as the correct performance
of a role: ruler, parent, child, teacher, friend. As code: role
tables, each with prescribed behaviors relative to other roles.
Rituals (li) as ordered sequences with pre- and post-conditions.
")

; -- write checkpoint 2.d --

; ------------------------------------------------------------
; 2.E — Dialectic and argumentation
; ------------------------------------------------------------

(subsection :id 2.e :title "Dialectic and argumentation"

  :prose "
Argumentation theory is one of the most mature areas of formal
philosophy — the tradition from Aristotle to modern computational
argumentation is unbroken, and the artifacts it produces are
directly usable.

**Abstract argumentation frameworks.** Phan Minh Dung, 'On the
Acceptability of Arguments and Its Fundamental Role in Nonmonotonic
Reasoning, Logic Programming and N-Person Games' (Artificial
Intelligence 77, 1995). Dung's paper defines an argumentation
framework as a directed graph of arguments where edges represent
attack. Extensions — grounded, preferred, stable, complete — are
sets of arguments that jointly resist attack. Dung's own paper
gives the algorithms; ~150 lines of Scheme implements them.
Dung's framework is one of the most cited papers in AI.

**Toulmin models.** Toulmin, _The Uses of Argument_ (Cambridge
1958). Every argument has claim, data, warrant, backing, qualifier,
rebuttal. A Toulmin-diagrammer takes an argument and structures it
into these roles; then critics can attack any role independently.
As Scheme records with slots, this is one page.

**Hegelian dialectic.** Hegel, _Phenomenology of Spirit_ (1807);
_Science of Logic_ (1812-16). Thesis, antithesis, synthesis — a
loop that generates a new position from a contradiction between
two prior ones. As code: given two propositions in tension, search
for a synthesis that preserves what is true in each while resolving
the contradiction. Not a solved problem; more like a search
scaffold that a hosted LLM can populate. But the SCAFFOLD is code.

**Socratic method.** Plato's dialogues (c. 380 BCE onward). Socrates
does not deliver theses; he asks questions that expose the
insufficiency of the interlocutor's answer. As code: a
question-generator that, given a claim, produces potential
counter-examples and requests-for-clarification. A Socratic tutor
system: several exist (Graesser et al.'s AutoTutor programme, see
Graesser, VanLehn, Rose, Jordan, Harter, 'Intelligent Tutoring
Systems with Conversational Dialogue,' AI Magazine 22, 2001). For
Sakura, Socratic questioning is a natural fit for teaching without
lecturing.

**Debate simulators and eristic dialectic.** Aristotle's _Topics_
and _Sophistical Refutations_ collect debate patterns and fallacy
types. A fallacy-detector over natural-language arguments is a
real subfield (see Habernal et al., 'Argumentation Mining,' ACL
tutorials). Small implementations of the Aristotelian topoi in
Scheme are pedagogical and useful.

**Nyaya five-limbed syllogism.** Gautama's _Nyaya Sutras_ (c. 200
BCE); Matilal, _The Character of Logic in India_ (SUNY 1998). The
Nyaya inference has five members: proposition, reason, example,
application, conclusion. It is more structured than the Aristotelian
syllogism and, interestingly, requires an example (a positive
instance) at inference time — a proto-case-based-reasoning shape.
As code: an inference procedure that requires a witness in its
knowledge base before it will conclude.
")

; -- write checkpoint 2.e --

; ------------------------------------------------------------
; 2.F — Symbolic AI and reasoning shape
; ------------------------------------------------------------

(subsection :id 2.f :title "Symbolic AI and reasoning shape"

  :prose "
Between 1958 and roughly 1990, artificial intelligence WAS
philosophically motivated symbolic computation. Every architecture
below has explicit philosophical parentage. All of them are still
directly relevant, and all of them are short enough to teach.

**Frame systems.** Marvin Minsky, 'A Framework for Representing
Knowledge' (MIT AI Memo 306, 1974; reprinted in Winston ed., _The
Psychology of Computer Vision_, McGraw-Hill 1975). A frame is a
data structure representing a stereotyped situation — a birthday
party, a hospital visit — with slots for participants and default
values. As Scheme records or hash tables, ~50 lines. Minsky's paper
is a philosophical document as much as a technical one; it argues
for structured knowledge over unstructured logic.

**Semantic networks.** M. Ross Quillian, 'Semantic Memory' (in
Minsky ed., _Semantic Information Processing_, MIT 1968). Nodes
are concepts, edges are typed relations (is-a, has-part, causes).
Spreading activation over the network gives you associative recall.
In Scheme this is a labelled graph with a BFS.

**Scripts.** Roger Schank and Robert Abelson, _Scripts, Plans,
Goals, and Understanding_ (Lawrence Erlbaum 1977). A script is an
ordered sequence of events characterizing a stereotyped activity
(the restaurant script: enter, sit, order, eat, pay, leave). Given
a partial observation, the script fills in the gaps by default.
Case-based-reasoning follows directly from this: retrieve the
closest matching prior case and adapt. Kolodner, _Case-Based
Reasoning_ (Morgan Kaufmann 1993), is the reference textbook.

**Analogical mapping.** Dedre Gentner, 'Structure-Mapping: A
Theoretical Framework for Analogy' (Cognitive Science 7, 1983);
Falkenhainer, Forbus, Gentner, 'The Structure-Mapping Engine:
Algorithm and Examples' (Artificial Intelligence 41, 1989). The
SME algorithm takes two structured representations and finds a
maximal structural correspondence — the analogy is the mapping.
About 400 lines of Scheme for a working SME. This is where Sakura's
'similar situation last time' shape properly comes from — not just
k-NN over embeddings, but structural analogy.

**Peirce's abduction as first-class inference.** Peirce, _Collected
Papers_ Vol. 5 (Harvard 1934). Abduction — inference to the best
explanation — is not a fixed algorithm but a stance: given a
surprising observation, generate hypotheses whose truth would
make the observation unsurprising, then evaluate them. In code,
abduction is generate-and-test with a plausibility scorer.
Josephson and Josephson, _Abductive Inference: Computation,
Philosophy, Technology_ (Cambridge 1994), collects the working
implementations. This is load-bearing for Sakura: her Cortex
retrievals ARE abductive generation, and her evidence-weighted
scoring IS abductive evaluation.

**Blackboard architectures.** Erman, Hayes-Roth, Lesser, Reddy,
'The Hearsay-II Speech-Understanding System' (Computing Surveys
12, 1980). Multiple specialist reasoners posting hypotheses to a
shared blackboard; a controller schedules which specialist runs
next. Philosophically: cognition as cooperating experts rather
than a single unified reasoner. Directly implementable and
directly relevant to how Sakura's cart-router should think.

**Production systems.** Newell and Simon, _Human Problem Solving_
(Prentice-Hall 1972); OPS5 (Forgy, 1981). If-then rules over a
working memory. This is the foundation of Soar (Laird, Newell,
Rosenbloom) and ACT-R (Anderson) — cognitive architectures that
are simultaneously psychological theories and running programs.
")

; -- write checkpoint 2.f --

; ------------------------------------------------------------
; 2.G — Phenomenology, intentionality, mind
; ------------------------------------------------------------

(subsection :id 2.g :title "Phenomenology, intentionality, and philosophy of mind"

  :prose "
This category sits at the edge of what code can express. Phenomenology
in the Husserlian and Heideggerian tradition explicitly resists
formalization. But several twentieth-century philosophers of mind
produced positions that ARE code-shaped, either as models or as
methodological stances a program can enact.

**Dennett's intentional stance.** Daniel Dennett, _The Intentional
Stance_ (MIT 1987). Treating a system as if it had beliefs, desires,
and rationality is a predictive strategy — you adopt the stance
because it works, not because you have decided the system 'really
has' beliefs. As code: given a system's behavior, fit a
belief-desire model that best predicts it (inverse planning; see
Baker, Saxe, Tenenbaum, 'Action Understanding as Inverse
Planning,' Cognition 113, 2009). The whole line of theory-of-mind
computational modelling implements the intentional stance.

**Multiple drafts model.** Dennett, _Consciousness Explained_
(Little, Brown 1991). Consciousness is not a Cartesian theater
watched by a single observer — it is a stream of concurrent
narrative drafts, some of which get amplified into what we report.
As code: multiple parallel hypothesis-generators; the winner is
whichever draft best fits ongoing input under a fitness function.
The predictive-coding architectures currently popular in
computational neuroscience (Friston, 'The Free-Energy Principle,'
Nature Reviews Neuroscience 11, 2010) are close cousins.

**Heterophenomenology.** Dennett, ibid. and 'Who's on First?
Heterophenomenology Explained' (JCS 10, 2003). Treating a subject's
own reports as data — not as authoritative revelations of what is
'really' going on, but as evidence to be interpreted alongside
behavior and physiology. As code: a data-collection discipline
that logs self-reports as observations with provenance, never as
oracle. This is exactly Sakura's stance on her own inner state:
report functional analogs, don't overclaim.

**Extended mind.** Clark and Chalmers, 'The Extended Mind'
(Analysis 58, 1998); Clark, _Supersizing the Mind_ (Oxford 2008).
Cognition extends into the tools and environment the agent uses.
As code: an architecture where memory is explicitly a graph of
external stores (files, notes, tools, other agents) that
participate in reasoning as first-class citizens. Cortex is
extended-mind theory made concrete.

**Enactivism.** Varela, Thompson, Rosch, _The Embodied Mind_ (MIT
1991); Thompson, _Mind in Life_ (Harvard 2007). Cognition emerges
from an organism's embodied engagement with its world. As code:
robotic and simulated-agent architectures where perception and
action are tightly coupled and representations are minimal
(Brooks, 'Intelligence Without Representation,' Artificial
Intelligence 47, 1991). Sakura, being disembodied, has a bounded
version of this — her 'body' is her verb set and the world she
acts on is the store and the cart.
")

; -- write checkpoint 2.g --

; ------------------------------------------------------------
; 2.H — Continental philosophy and text-manipulation shapes
; ------------------------------------------------------------

(subsection :id 2.h :title "Continental philosophy and text-manipulation shapes"

  :prose "
Continental philosophy in the deconstructive and structuralist
modes operates on text and sign. It resists formal capture at the
top level — Derrida in particular argued that any formalization
already presupposes what he was trying to problematize. But at the
mechanism level several moves are directly implementable, and
implementing them is a legitimate way to understand the
philosophical claim.

**Derrida's différance.** Derrida, _Of Grammatology_ (Minuit 1967;
English JHU 1976); 'Différance' in _Margins of Philosophy_ (Minuit
1972; English Chicago 1982). Meaning is deferred — a sign points
to other signs, which point to other signs, without ever landing
on a self-standing signified. As code: implement a semantic
network where 'meaning' is a walk of bounded depth through
neighbors, and the 'meaning' of a term is the SET of walks, not
any single terminal. This is what modern word embeddings capture
in aggregate; Derrida wrote about the phenomenon fifty years before
Mikolov trained word2vec.

**Structuralist axes: metaphor and metonymy.** Jakobson, 'Two
Aspects of Language and Two Types of Aphasic Disturbances' (1956,
in _Fundamentals of Language_, Mouton 1971). Lacan picked this up
in _Ecrits_ (Seuil 1966; English Norton 2006): metaphor as
substitution on the paradigmatic (vertical) axis, metonymy as
combination on the syntagmatic (horizontal) axis. As code:
substitution tables (metaphor) and adjacency-graph walks
(metonymy) as two different retrieval strategies. This is a
formally precise implementation of the Lacanian claim.

**Barthes' S/Z.** Roland Barthes, _S/Z_ (Seuil 1970; English Hill
and Wang 1974). A close reading of Balzac's Sarrasine using five
codes (hermeneutic, semantic, symbolic, proairetic, cultural).
As code: an annotation system over a text with these five
channels, plus a coder trained on Barthes's examples. Real
literary-analysis pipelines have done this at small scale (see
Jockers, _Macroanalysis_, Illinois 2013).

**Foucault's discourse analysis.** Foucault, _The Archaeology of
Knowledge_ (Gallimard 1969; English Pantheon 1972). Not code
directly. But corpus-linguistic tools that track term frequency,
collocation, and shifts in usage over time (see Michel et al.,
'Quantitative Analysis of Culture Using Millions of Digitized
Books,' Science 331, 2011 — the Google Ngrams paper) are what
Foucault was doing by hand, in miniature.
")

; -- write checkpoint 2.h --

; ------------------------------------------------------------
; 2.I — Non-Western and comparative traditions
; ------------------------------------------------------------

(subsection :id 2.i :title "Non-Western and comparative traditions"

  :prose "
Several non-Western philosophical traditions produced formal or
proto-formal artifacts that translate to code as cleanly as any
Western system. Naming them belongs in a serious survey.

**Nagarjuna's tetralemma (catuskoti).** Nagarjuna, _Mulamadhyamakakarika_
(c. 200 CE); Garfield's translation _The Fundamental Wisdom of the
Middle Way_ (Oxford 1995). The four positions on any proposition P:
P, not-P, both, neither. This is a four-valued logic that has been
formalized by Priest (_Beyond the Limits of Thought_, Oxford 2nd
ed. 2002) as a paraconsistent extension. In Scheme, truth values
are drawn from a four-element set and the connectives are extended
accordingly.

**Indian logic (Nyaya).** Already mentioned under 2.E for the
five-limbed syllogism. Additional artifacts: the theory of
inferential fallacies (hetvabhasa) — five recognized types — is
a taxonomy that translates directly to a fallacy-checker. The
theory of perception (pratyaksa) as a stage-based process
(sense-object contact, indeterminate cognition, determinate
cognition) has a pipeline shape.

**Confucian role ethics.** Already covered under 2.D. Add: the
Analects itself is a compact enough text that a structured
representation (speaker, addressee, situation, saying, commentary)
gives you a queryable ethical case-base.

**Ibn Rushd (Averroes).** _Fasl al-Maqal_ (c. 1179); Hourani's
translation _On the Harmony of Religion and Philosophy_ (Luzac
1961). Ibn Rushd systematized Aristotelian logic in the Islamic
tradition; his commentaries on Aristotle's Prior Analytics were
the standard medieval source. Translation to code inherits all
the Aristotelian syllogistic machinery, plus specific innovations
in modal and hypothetical syllogism.

**Ubuntu.** Already covered under 2.D. Add: the relational-network
structure lends itself to graph algorithms — betweenness centrality
as a proxy for 'connectedness in community' — but the philosophy
warns against reducing personhood to a graph metric. That WARNING
is itself philosophically significant when you code with it.
")

; -- write checkpoint 2.i --

; ============================================================
; SECTION 3 — Which of the 16 philosophers produce code-shaped artifacts
; ============================================================

(section :n 3 :title "Which of the 16 (+ Socrates) produce code-shaped artifacts"

  :prose "
One paragraph per philosopher: what code-shaped artifact do they
produce, which Scheme feature best expresses it, and one concrete
project shape or verb design.

**Jung.** Archetypal identity of objects. As code: a tagged-object
system where objects carry archetypal tags (mother, trickster, hero,
shadow, self) with strength scores. Best Scheme feature: symbols
and property lists. Project: an archetype-detector over a Cortex
of user narratives — given a story fragment, propose which archetypes
are active. Composes with narrative generation.

**Wittgenstein-early (Tractatus).** The world as facts, propositions
as pictures of facts. As code: a fact base with atomic propositions
as tuples, compound propositions as truth-functional combinations.
Best Scheme feature: quoted S-expressions as first-class terms.
Project: a picture-theory-of-meaning implementation — atomic facts
are relations between objects, sentences are structures over those
relations, evaluate truth by isomorphism.

**Wittgenstein-late (Investigations).** Language games. As code:
a game-registry where each game has moves, roles, and success
conditions, but no attempt to give a general theory of all games.
Best Scheme feature: modular records with per-game predicates.
Project: a specific-game engine for shop conversations that DOES
NOT try to generalize.

**Lacan.** Metaphor and metonymy as substitution and combination
axes; the sliding signifier. As code: two retrieval strategies over
a lexicon — substitution tables for metaphor, adjacency graphs for
metonymy. Best Scheme feature: association lists plus graph walks.
Project: a two-axis word-associator that Sakura can consult when
writing prose, giving her metaphoric AND metonymic variants of
a term.

**Peirce.** Abduction. Also his semiotic triad (sign, object,
interpretant). As code: an inference engine that generates
candidate explanations for surprising observations and scores them
by prior plausibility and explanatory scope. Best Scheme feature:
continuations for non-deterministic search + macros for pattern
languages. Project: an abductive-reasoner verb `abduce/hypotheses`
that takes evidence and returns ranked hypotheses. Load-bearing
for Sakura.

**Popper.** Falsifiability. Conjecture and refutation as the shape
of scientific reasoning. As code: for every hypothesis a program
entertains, generate a would-be-observation that would falsify it,
and check whether such an observation is available. Best Scheme
feature: higher-order functions to represent hypothesis-generators
and falsifier-generators. Project: a Popperian scientist verb —
given a claim, produce a falsifier attempt and report success or
failure.

**Freud.** Manifest and latent content; symptomatic reading. As
code: a two-layer representation of utterances — surface form
and inferred latent content — with rules connecting them (slips,
displacements, condensations). Best Scheme feature: pattern-matching
with residues. Project: a hedge-detector that reads latent worry
in surface-neutral utterances (Alfred wanted this for Sakura's
customer-service disposition).

**Searle.** Speech acts. Chinese Room as methodological caution.
As code: an utterance classifier over Searle's five categories
(assertive, directive, commissive, expressive, declarative) with
felicity conditions per act. Best Scheme feature: multiple
dispatch or a case discriminator on utterance form. Project: the
`read-utterance` verb already in Sakura's design — classify then
dispatch. Chinese Room: the RESIDUAL awareness that classification
is not comprehension. Ships as commentary in the file.

**Grice.** Cooperative principle; four maxims. As code: a
maxim-checker that scores utterances on Quantity, Quality,
Relation, Manner and flags implicatures. Best Scheme feature:
predicate combinators. Project: a Gricean quality-check on
Sakura's own outbound utterances before she says them.

**Derrida.** Différance — meaning as deferral. As code: a semantic
network with bounded-depth walks; meaning as the multi-walk envelope.
Best Scheme feature: lazy sequences (streams). Project: a
delayed-binding lexicon — words don't have meanings, they have
walks; asking for a meaning returns a stream. Composes with Lacan.

**Quine.** Ontological commitment; the web of belief. As code: a
knowledge base with belief-revision (AGM). Best Scheme feature:
persistent maps + versioning. Project: a belief-revision engine
that logs which beliefs were dropped in response to which new
evidence — Quine's holism made visible.

**Descartes.** Method of doubt; cogito. As code: bootstrapping a
knowledge base from first principles, with each addition
justified by a proof from prior additions. Best Scheme feature:
proof objects as terms. Project: a Cartesian foundationalist —
given a claim, trace it back to indubitable premises or fail.
(The failure IS the philosophically interesting output.)

**Sartre.** Radical freedom; being-for-itself vs. being-in-itself;
bad faith. Least directly code-shaped of the sixteen. But: a
choice-tracker that records every branch-point in a program's
execution as a choice with alternatives could stand in for the
existentialist emphasis on choice. Project: an execution-trace
that surfaces choices explicitly to the user, for pedagogical
transparency ('here is where the program could have gone
differently').

**Rawls.** Veil of ignorance; original position; maximin. As code:
an anonymization function over policies and a maximin evaluator.
Best Scheme feature: higher-order functions over policy objects.
Project: a fairness verb — given a proposed decision that identifies
individuals, strip identifiers, evaluate across the population,
and flag if outcomes are unacceptable for the worst-off. Rawlsian
audit for any cart that touches multiple parties.

**Aristotle.** Practical syllogism; virtue ethics; categorization
(the ten categories). As code: syllogistic engine, character-vector
agent, and a taxonomic tree. Best Scheme feature: records with
inheritance. Project: a phronetic agent that, given a situation
and a character vector, produces the mean-between-extremes action.
Also the categorization scheme for Sakura's items — Aristotle's
categories map surprisingly well onto product taxonomy.

**Levinas.** Face of the Other as ethical foundation. As code: a
required 'encounter' step in every ethically-loaded operation —
before aggregation or decision, the individual is presented as
face. Best Scheme feature: dynamic-wind or context-manager idioms.
Project: a moral-audit wrapper that ensures no cart operates on
individuals purely as instances of a category — a Levinasian check
in every mass-action path.

**Dennett.** Intentional stance; heterophenomenology; multiple
drafts. As code: a belief-desire modeler (inverse planning), a
self-report logger with provenance, and a multi-hypothesis stream
with fitness-based selection. Best Scheme feature: streams +
higher-order agent models. Project: Sakura's introspection logs
implemented as heterophenomenology — reports treated as data with
timestamps and confidence, never as authoritative revelation.

**Socrates (sprinkled).** Question generation; refutation. As code:
a question-generator that, given a proposed claim, produces
counter-examples and clarification requests. Best Scheme feature:
lazy generators of hypothetical objections. Project: a Socratic
tutor mode Sakura can enter when a user is confused — she doesn't
lecture, she asks.
")

; -- write checkpoint 3 --

; ============================================================
; SECTION 4 — "Any programming language and translate"
; ============================================================

(section :n 4 :title "Philosophical work that lives in other languages and can be translated"

  :prose "
Alfred added: *if any is done in any programming language at all and
we have support for it and can translate.* Substantial bodies of
philosophical work exist in languages other than Scheme, most of them
translatable. The following are the productive sources.

**Prolog** — the natural home of logic programming, and by extension
of large chunks of analytic philosophy in executable form. Any
Prolog program that consists of Horn clauses translates directly
to Scheme via the mini-Prolog interpreter (see the sibling document
25-projects-for-sakura-scheme-2026-07-14.slat, project 2). The
canonical corpus:

  - Bratko, _Prolog Programming for Artificial Intelligence_
    (Addison-Wesley 4th ed. 2011) — expert systems, planning,
    game trees, natural language parsing.
  - Blackburn and Bos, _Representation and Inference for Natural
    Language_ (CSLI 2005) — Montague semantics, discourse
    representation theory, inference.
  - Sterling and Shapiro, _The Art of Prolog_ (MIT 2nd ed. 1994) —
    reasoning about programs, meta-interpreters.

Everything in these three books ports to Sakura Scheme in
paragraph-sized chunks. Blackburn and Bos in particular is a direct
translation of philosophy-of-language into working code.

**Coq / Agda / Lean / Isabelle** — proof assistants. The corpus of
formalized mathematics and philosophy in these languages is now
enormous. Immediately relevant:

  - The Coq'Art book (Bertot and Casteran, _Interactive Theorem
    Proving and Program Development_, Springer 2004).
  - The Software Foundations series (Pierce et al.) — programming
    language semantics as executable proofs.
  - Isabelle formalizations of Godel's ontological argument for
    God (Benzmuller and Woltzenlogel Paleo, ECAI 2014) — an
    actual piece of philosophy machine-checked.
  - Formalizations of Kant's categorical imperative in Coq
    (existence acknowledged in the Machine Ethics literature).

Direct translation of dependent-type proofs to Sakura Scheme is
not possible without adding a type checker. But the PROPOSITIONS —
the theorem statements and the informal proof steps — translate
into a Scheme natural-deduction checker without difficulty.

**Python and modern natural-language pipelines.** The philosophy is
mostly indirect (methodology encoded in library architecture) but
the artifacts are heavy:

  - SymPy — computer algebra; ports to Scheme via the
    symbolic-differentiation shape of SICP §2.3.
  - NLTK, spaCy — annotated corpora and grammatical analysis;
    port pattern-by-pattern.
  - AllenNLP, natural language inference libraries (SNLI, MultiNLI
    benchmarks; see Bowman et al., 'A Large Annotated Corpus for
    Learning Natural Language Inference,' EMNLP 2015) — the
    entailment problem that mid-century philosophers of language
    formalized is now a machine-learning benchmark.

**Rosetta Code and Programming Languages: Application and
Interpretation (PLAI).** Shriram Krishnamurthi's _Programming
Languages: Application and Interpretation_ (2007, free online)
gives Scheme (Racket) implementations of most of the shapes
this document names. It is one of the most direct sources for
translation work.

**Historical Lisp corpora.** The primary academic AI literature
from 1958 through the late 1980s was in Lisp and translates
verbatim. Specific mines:

  - Norvig, _Paradigms of Artificial Intelligence Programming:
    Case Studies in Common Lisp_ (Morgan Kaufmann 1992) — GPS,
    Eliza, small Prolog, small OPS-5, PATR grammar, symbolic
    integrator, waltz-line-labeling. The whole book ports to
    Sakura Scheme.
  - Winston and Horn, _LISP_ (Addison-Wesley 3rd ed. 1989) —
    frames, rules, forward and backward chaining.
  - Steele, _Common Lisp the Language_ (Digital Press 2nd ed.
    1990) — for reference when Norvig code uses CL-specific
    macros.
  - Sussman and Wisdom, _Structure and Interpretation of Classical
    Mechanics_ (MIT 2nd ed. 2014) — symbolic mathematical
    physics; ports back to Sakura Scheme because SICM is already
    a Scheme dialect (scmutils).

**Argumentation-theory implementations.** Dung frameworks have
public reference implementations in Java, Python, and Prolog
(ASPARTIX, ConArg, TweetyProject). Port the algorithms; they're
straightforward graph computations.

**Bayesian modelling.** Church (Goodman, Mansinghka, Roy, Bonawitz,
Tenenbaum, 'Church: A Language for Generative Models,' UAI 2008)
IS a probabilistic Scheme; every Church program lifts into Sakura
Scheme once we add sampling and observe primitives. Its successor
WebPPL (dippl.org) is JavaScript-based; the models translate.
Practically all of the 'probabilistic language of thought' research
programme (Tenenbaum, Goodman, and collaborators) sits here.
")

; -- write checkpoint 4 --

